context: Of the territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union between 1939 and 1940, the region around Białystok and a minor part of Galicia east of the San river around Przemyśl were returned to the <a0_0><b3_0><b4_0>Polish state<b4_0/><b3_0/><a0_0/> at the end of World War II. Of all other territories annexed by the USSR in 1939–40, the ones detached from <b5_0>Finland <a1_0>(Karelia, Petsamo), Estonia (Ingrian area and Petseri County) and Latvia (Abrene)<b5_0/> remained part of the Russian Federation<a1_0/>, the successor state of the Soviet Union, after 1991. <a2_0><b6_0><b7_0>Northern Bukovina, Southern Bessarabia and Hertza<b6_0/><a2_0/> remain part of Ukraine<b7_0/>.
